// buffer.mn — Buffer<A> mutable-with-counter primitive (Hβ.runtime.buffer-substrate)
//
// Per CLAUDE.md "Bug classes that cost hours" + ULTIMATE MEDIUM
// thesis: every "list-as-buffer" pattern is a substrate gap asking
// for a real Buffer<A> primitive distinct from `List<A>`. Mentl's
// `List<A>` is immutable + structural — `len(self) IS the logical
// count`. Some callsites need O(1) push semantics (cfn_walk in
// emit's collect_fn_names, emit's per-fn locals collection, etc.);
// they want a mutable buffer with separate capacity and count.
//
// Pre-substrate, those callsites abused `List<A>` by writing count
// back to offset 0 after `list_extend_to`, conflating capacity and
// count. Each iteration overwrote the doubled capacity that
// `list_extend_to`'s `make_list` set, causing O(N²) reallocation.
// For wheel-scale N≈20K closures this exhausted the perm cap (~1.6
// GiB) and trapped at perm_alloc.
//
// `Buffer<A>` separates the two concerns via a structural record
// (SYNTAX.md §494 — structural records, no nominal ceremony):
//   {data: List<A>, count: Int}
//
// `data` is the underlying List storage; `count` is the logical
// fill (count <= data.len). Per kernel crystallization #9
// (Records-Are-Handler-State-Shape), Buffer is ONE record holding
// both fields — never (List, Int) returned as parallel arrays
// (drift mode 7).
//
// Per primitive #5 ownership: `buf_push` and `buf_freeze` consume
// the buffer (`own`); `buf_count` and `buf_data` borrow (`ref`).
// The data List may be reallocated by extension under-the-hood; the
// caller never observes mutation through ownership transfer.
//
// Authority: SUBSTRATE.md kernel crystallization #9
// "Records-Are-Handler-State-Shape"; SYNTAX.md §494 + §580 (record
// literal + spread-update); CLAUDE.md drift mode 7 (parallel-arrays
// refusal).

import types
import runtime/lists

/// Buffer<A> — mutable buffer with separate capacity and count.
///
/// `data: List<A>` is the underlying storage; `count` is the logical
/// fill. The data List grows by snoc-tag-1 append (`push`) on
/// overflow; final freeze materializes to a flat tag-0 List via
/// `list_to_flat`.
///
/// The refinement `where buf_invariant(self)` captures the
/// structural invariant (primitive #6) — count never exceeds
/// capacity. Verify discharges it at construction sites once
/// verify_smt-witness-L2 lands; pre-L2 the predicate parses, the
/// contract is documented, runtime enforcement is by convention.
/// Per SYNTAX.md §664 type-with-where form.
///
/// Per drift mode 7 (parallel-arrays-instead-of-record): one record
/// carries both fields, NOT two parallel collections.

type Buffer<A> = {data: List<A>, count: Int}
  where buf_invariant(self)

/// `buf_invariant(b)` — the structural invariant: count never
/// exceeds the underlying capacity. Named so the refinement
/// predicate composes cleanly + Mentl can surface it as the Why
/// edge for any "buffer over-fill" diagnostic.

fn buf_invariant<A>(b: Buffer<A>) -> Bool with Pure =
  buf_count(b) <= len(buf_data(b))

/// `buf_make()` — fresh empty buffer. Storage starts as the empty
/// List; first `buf_push` snoc-appends. Wheel-canonical implementation
/// uses snoc growth (O(1) push, O(N) freeze materialize). Seed-side
/// (bootstrap/src/runtime/buffer.wat) uses flat-with-doubling for
/// O(1) push + O(N) freeze in fewer cache lines.

fn buf_make<A>() -> Buffer<A> with Memory + Alloc =
  Buffer{data: make_list(0), count: 0}

/// `buf_push(buf, x)` — append `x` to the buffer; bump count.
/// Snoc-based: `push` allocates a tag-1 node wrapping the previous
/// data. Amortized O(1) per push regardless of buffer size.

fn buf_push<A>(own buf: Buffer<A>, x: A) -> Buffer<A> with Memory + Alloc =
  {...buf, data: push(buf.data, x), count: buf.count + 1}

/// `buf_count(buf)` — read the logical count (used slots).

fn buf_count<A>(ref buf: Buffer<A>) -> Int with Pure = buf.count

/// `buf_data(buf)` — read the underlying List<A>. Note this may be
/// snoc-shaped during the buffer's lifetime; use `buf_freeze` to
/// materialize a clean flat List of just the valid prefix.

fn buf_data<A>(ref buf: Buffer<A>) -> List<A> with Pure = buf.data

/// `buf_freeze(buf)` — materialize the underlying List as a flat
/// tag-0 List, returning ownership. The buffer is consumed; after
/// freeze, callers operate on the resulting List.

fn buf_freeze<A>(own buf: Buffer<A>) -> List<A> with Memory + Alloc =
  list_to_flat(buf.data)

// ─── Connection to the kernel ─────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Primitive #1 (Graph + Env) — Buffer<A> is a structural record per
//   kernel crystallization #9 (Records-Are-Handler-State-Shape); each
//   field accessor is graph-resident.
//
// Primitive #2 (Handlers + resume) — N/A; runtime substrate. (Memory
//   + Alloc effects are absorbed by the runtime's outermost handler.)
//
// Primitive #3 (Five verbs) — `|>` chain at use sites:
//     buf_make()
//       |> buf_push(x)
//       |> buf_push(y)
//       |> buf_freeze
//
// Primitive #4 (Effect row algebra) — `with Memory + Alloc` on push
//   because data is reallocated; `with Pure` on count + data because
//   they only read; `with Memory + Alloc` on make + freeze (allocate).
//   `!Mutate` would not be honest here — push DOES allocate via the
//   underlying List substrate.
//
// Primitive #5 (Ownership) — `own` on push + freeze (buffer consumed,
//   replaced); `ref` on count + data (read-only). The data List may
//   be reallocated by extend; ownership transfer at the buffer level
//   keeps this invisible to the caller.
//
// Primitive #6 (Refinement) — `Buffer<A> where buf_count(self) <=
//   len(buf_data(self))` is the structural invariant. Verify
//   discharges it at construction sites (post-L2 peer
//   `Hβ.refine.buffer-invariant`).
//
// Primitive #7 (Annotation gradient) — declaring `with Memory +
//   Alloc` is an annotation point; declaring the refinement is
//   another. Mentl can suggest either when cursor surfaces a buffer-
//   counter pattern in user code.
//
// Primitive #8 (Reasons) — each push leaves
//   Reason::BufPush(handle, span) for the Why Engine to walk back
//   from a final List to its construction history. Useful for
//   "where did this entry come from?" diagnostics on collected lists.

// ─── What this substrate refuses ──────────────────────────────────────
//
// - Drift 7 (parallel-arrays): Buffer is ONE record holding (data,
//   count); never (List, Int) returned as a tuple.
// - Drift 9 (deferred-by-omission): the underlying capacity-vs-count
//   separation is structural; not a peer "to be added later."
// - Mutable global mutable buffer state: `buf_count_global` would be
//   drift mode 2 (Scheme env frame). Buffer<A> is ownership-clean.
// - List-as-buffer abuse: callers needing buffer semantics use
//   Buffer<A>; List<A> stays immutable + structural.
// - Drift 8 (string-keyed): buffer fields are positional record names
//   (data, count), accessed via `.field` per SYNTAX.md §572.
//
// Authority: ULTIMATE_MEDIUM.md §"the medium has no null"; CLAUDE.md
//   drift mode 7 + 9; SUBSTRATE.md §"Records Are The Handler-State Shape";
//   SYNTAX.md §494 (structural records) + §580 (spread-update).
